version: 1
display_name: VCFR-9X-000055 - The VMware Cloud Foundation NSX Tier-0 Gateway must be configured to use a unique password for each autonomous system (AS) with which it peers.
global_description: |-
  If the same keys are used between eBGP neighbors, the chance of a hacker compromising any of the BGP sessions increases. It is possible that a malicious user exists in one autonomous system who would know the key used for the eBGP session. This user would then be able to hijack BGP sessions with other trusted neighbors.
osfinger: []  # API/proxy-managed control; not tied to a minion OS grain
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - VCFR-9X-000055
  srg:
    - SRG-NET-000230-RTR-000002
  cci:
    - CCI-001184
  nist:
    - SC-23
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_nsx_routing:
    type: custom
    desc: The VMware Cloud Foundation NSX Tier-0 Gateway must be configured to use a unique password for each autonomous system (AS) with which it peers.
    control_id: VCFR-9X-000055
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      If the Tier-0 Gateway is not using BGP, this is Not Applicable.

      Since the NSX Tier-0 Gateway does not reveal the current password, interview the router administrator to determine if unique passwords are being used.

      If unique passwords are not being used for each AS, this is a finding.
    rationale: |-
      If the same keys are used between eBGP neighbors, the chance of a hacker compromising any of the BGP sessions increases. It is possible that a malicious user exists in one autonomous system who would know the key used for the eBGP session. This user would then be able to hijack BGP sessions with other trusted neighbors.
    remediation: |-
      To set authentication for BGP neighbors do the following:

      From the NSX Manager web interface, go to Networking >> Connectivity >> Tier-0 Gateways, and expand the target Tier-0 gateway.

      Expand BGP. Next to BGP Neighbors, click on the number present to open the dialog, then select "Edit" on the target BGP Neighbor.

      Expand "BGP", click the number next to "BGP Neighbors". Select "Edit" on the target BGP neighbor.

      Under Timers & Password, enter a password up to 20 characters that is different from other autonomous systems, and then click "Save".
